05875nam a22007575i 9781479862634DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798626347 a10.18574/nyu/9781479862634.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548173  a(OCoLC)1005979067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0370302bisacsh04a297.097304aThe Practice of Islam in America :bAn Introduction /ced. by Edward E. Curtis IV. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Prayer and pilgrimage -- t1. Salah: daily prayers in Muslim America -- t2. Dhikr: remembering the divine -- t3. Hajj: the pilgrimage -- tPart II. Holidays -- t4. Ramadan, Eid al-fitr, and eid al-Adha: fasting and feasting -- t5. Ashura: commemorating Imam Husayn -- t6. Milad/Mawlid: celebrating the prophet Muhammad’s birthday -- tPart III. Life cycle rituals -- t7. Birth rituals: welcoming a child into the world -- t8. Weddings: love and mercy in marriage ceremonies -- t9. Funerals and death rites: honoring the departed -- tPart IV. Islamic ethics and religious culture -- t10. You can’t be human alone: philanthropy and social giving in Muslim communities -- t11. Food practices: the ethics of eating -- t12. The Qur’an: studying, embodying, and living with the word of god -- tAbout the editor -- tAbout the contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn introduction to the ways in which ordinary Muslim Americans practice their faith. Muslims have always been part of the United States, but very little is known about how Muslim Americans practice their religion. How do they pray? What’s it like to go on pilgrimage to Mecca? What rituals accompany the birth of a child, a wedding, or the death of a loved one? What holidays do Muslims celebrate and what charities do they support? How do they learn about the Qur’an? The Practice of Islam in America introduces readers to the way Islam is lived in the United States, offering vivid portraits of Muslim American life passages, ethical actions, religious holidays, prayer, pilgrimage, and other religious activities. It takes readers into homes, religious congregations, schools, workplaces, cemeteries, restaurants-and all the way to Mecca-to understand the diverse religious practices of Muslim Americans. Going beyond a theoretical discussion of what Muslims are supposed to do, this volume focuses on what they actually do. As the volume reveals, their religious practices are shaped by their racial and ethnic identity, their gender and sexual orientation, and their sectarian identity, among other social factors. Readers gain practical information about Islamic religion while also coming to understand how the day-to-day realities of American life shape Muslim American practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMuslims--United States. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh1 aAli, Muna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAslan, Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbett, Rosemary R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis IV, Edward E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCurtis, Maria F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlan, Magfirah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Juliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermansen, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHussain, Amir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Michael Muhammad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRashid, Hussein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalem, Jackleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWidmann Abraham, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072897240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479862634.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479862634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479862634/original  a978-3-11-072897-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles